====================================================
  SCIENTIFIC VERDICT
====================================================

OUTCOME: B (Manifold Quality Dependency) — NOT A (Universal Geometry)

The N/W density law is universal in SHAPE (all encoders flatten at W >= 128),
but the LEVEL of recall at plateau depends on the encoder's semantic manifold
quality — specifically, how well statement-query similarity survives the
random bottleneck projection.

Key findings:
1. Random Projection achieves 100% because queries = statements + noise(σ=0.05),
   so statement-query pairs are near-identical vectors. This is the geometric
   upper bound when semantic distance ≈ 0.
2. MiniLM dominates semantic encoders because its 384d manifold preserves
   statement-query paraphrase similarity best under random projection.
3. MPNet and E5-base (768d) underperform 384d encoders, suggesting their
   semantic manifold has higher intrinsic curvature or sparser structure that
   random linear projections damage more severely.
4. The density law N/W governs the SHAPE of capacity scaling across all
   encoders, but the LEVEL is an encoder-specific constant determined by
   manifold geometry.
